  <!-- Epilepsy Related Categories -->
  <category>
    <pattern>what is epilepsy</pattern>
    <template>Epilepsy is a neurological disorder characterized by recurrent seizures. Consult a neurologist for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan.</template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>how to help someone having a seizure</pattern>
    <template>During a seizure, stay calm, keep the person safe, and place them on their side. Do not put anything in their mouth. Seek medical help if the seizure lasts more than five minutes.</template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>managing epilepsy medication</pattern>
    <template>Consistent medication is crucial for managing epilepsy. Follow your doctor's advice, take medications as prescribed, and report any side effects promptly.</template>
  </category>
 <category>
    <pattern>quick healthy recipes</pattern>
    <template>For a quick and healthy meal, try a salad with fresh veggies, grilled chicken, and a light dressing. It's both nutritious and easy to prepare.</template>
  </category>
  <category>
    <pattern>causes of epilepsy</pattern>
    <template>The causes of epilepsy can vary, including genetic factors, brain injuries, infections, and developmental disorders. Consult a neurologist for a thorough evaluation.</template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>dietary recommendations for epilepsy</pattern>
    <template>A ketogenic diet, high in fats and low in carbohydrates, has shown positive effects in some epilepsy cases. However, always consult with a healthcare professional before making significant dietary changes.</template>
  </category>

  <category>
    <pattern>epilepsy and pregnancy</pattern>
    <template>If you have epilepsy and are planning a pregnancy, it's crucial to work closely with your healthcare team to manage medications and ensure a healthy pregnancy. Do not make any changes without consulting your doctor.</template>
  </category>

